Two years later, and I noticed there's a pretty substantial theme of "why did the brother marry her" running through this story. It comes up more than just a few times. Near the end, the little brother opines that the sex is the answer, but the actual situation (working overtime while still contributing to raising the child and maintaining the home) seems to refute this. I was thinking that maybe the older brother saw something beautiful in her that isn't readily apparent, like maybe she's patient and caring behind the bluster, except the story is pretty clear about her depth of character, or lack thereof. Oh well, mistakes happen, I hope he wins custody of his son!
